<section xml:id="section-arithmetic">

    <title>Arithmetic with Signed Numbers, Decimals, and Natural Exponents</title>
   
    <introduction>
        <p>From daily life, most of us are familiar with how the basic mathematical operations<mdash />addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division<mdash />work. In this section, we'll discuss each operation briefly, and develop a few techniques to help us make sense of these operations as we study algebra.</p>

        <p>We've all seen positive and negative numbers in math classes growing up, but few of us have any need to deal with negative numbers in daily life. We'll also discuss techniques that will help us make sense of how negative numbers affect the basic operations.</p>
    </introduction>
    <subsection>
        <title>Addition</title>
        <p>When we're considering counts, <term>addition</term> simply means <q>more.</q> Starting with five apples, then getting three more gives<me>
\text{&#127823; &#127823; &#127823;} + \text{&#127823; &#127823;} = \text{&#127823; &#127823; &#127823; &#127823; &#127823;}
</me></p>

        <p>It doesn't matter if we add two apples to three apples or three apples to two apples, either way we end up with five apples. Order isn't important for addition. When the order of an operation doesn't matter, mathematicians say the operation is <term>commutative</term>.</p>
        
        <p>For small <term>whole numbers</term> (0, 1, 2, 3, 4, etc.) we can add by counting. For larger whole numbers, we use an algorithm to add by hand. Over the centuries, people have developed many algorithms that work. Adding <m>697</m> apples to <m>223</m> apples, here are two possible algorithms:</p>
        
        <todo>animated versions of algorithms? perhaps as "solutions"?</todo>
        <sidebyside>
            <p><me>
                \begin{array}{rrrr}
                \amp_1 \amp_1 \amp   \\
                \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                \hline{}
                \amp 9 \amp 2 \amp 0
                \end{array}
           </me></p>
           <p><me>
                \begin{array}{rrr}
                6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                \hline{}
                8 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                \hline{}
                9 \amp 2 \amp 0
                \end{array}
           </me></p> 
        </sidebyside>

        <p>Do you see how both algorithms work? (One should be familiar, the other might require some thought.) Whether we add by hand or use technology (calculator, computer, cell phone, etc.) we have <m>697 + 223 = 920</m> apples.</p> 
        
        <p>In mathematics, we call each number being added together a <term>term</term> or a <term>summand</term>, and the result of addition is called a <term>sum</term>. In this PCC course, you'll be required to perform calculations by hand on exams. Here are a few practice problems.</p>
        
        <exercise>
            <statement><p>Perform each addition by hand, then check your results. 
                <ol>
                    <li>Add <m>1</m> to <m>9</m>.</li>
                    <li>Add <m>12</m> to <m>98</m>.</li>
                    <li>Add <m>123456</m> to <m>987654</m>.</li>
                    <li>Add <m>34.67</m> to <m>81.53</m>.</li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>

            <solution><p>
                <ol>
                    <li>10</li>
                    <li><m>110</m></li>
                    <li><m>1111110</m></li>
                    <li><m>116.2</m></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Subtraction</title>
        
        <p>Whenever we end up with <q>less</q> or <q>fewer</q> of some amount, we can use <term>subtraction</term>.<me>\text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} - \text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} = \text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} \text{&#128028;} </me></p>

        <p>Again, if the values are small we can find the <term>difference</term> of two terms by counting. Unlike addition, the order of subtraction matters. Reversing the order of <m>6 - 2 = 4</m> ants doesn't make sense. Starting with <m>4</m> ants, we cannot have <m>6</m> fewer ants. Though there are situations where subtracting a larger number from a smaller number makes sense, the order of subtraction does matter. Subtraction is <em>not</em> a commutative operation.</p>

        <p>For larger values, there are subtraction algorithms that work well for computing differences by hand.</p>

        <sidebyside>
        <p><me>
        \begin{array}{rrrr}
          \amp 6 \amp 2 \amp 8 \\
        - \amp 5 \amp 5 \amp 0 \\
        \hline{}
          \amp   \amp 7 \amp 8
        \end{array}
        </me></p>
        <p><me>
        \begin{array}{rrr}
        6 \amp 2 \amp 8 \\
        5 \amp 5 \amp 0 \\
        \hline{}
        1 \amp 2 \amp 8 \\
          \amp 5 \amp 0 \\
        \hline{}
          \amp 7 \amp 8        
        \end{array}
        </me></p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>Do you see how these algorithms work? (Again, one should be familiar.) Time for more practice doing arithmetic by hand.</p>

        <exercise>
            <statement><p>Perform each subtraction by hand, then check your results. 
                <ol>
                    <li>Subtract <m>99</m> from  <m>1000</m>.</li>
                    <li>Subtract <m>999</m> from  <m>100000</m>.</li>
                    <li>Subtract <m>0.87</m> from  <m>1</m>.</li>
                    <li>Subtract <m>492.3</m> from  <m>1023.1</m>.</li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>

            <solution><p>
                <ol>
                    <li><m>901</m></li>
                    <li>99001</li>
                    <li><m>0.13</m></li>
                    <li><m>1530.8</m></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Multiplication</title>
        
        <p>There's more than one way to think about <term>multiplication</term>. For counts, multiplication helps us compute the number of cats in the table below.</p>

        <table>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>If we notice three rows with four cats each, we have<me>4 + 4 + 4 = 4 \times 3 = 12 \text{ cats},</me> but if we notice four columns with three cats each, that's <me>3 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 3 \times 4 = 12 \text{ cats}.</me> Either way, multiplication can serve as shorthand for repeated addition. And it's clear that the order of the <term>factors</term> (the numbers we multiply together) has no effect on the value of the <term>product</term> (the result of multiplication). Muliplication, like addition, is a commutative operation.</p>

        <p>Multiplication isn't always shorthand for repeated addition. We also use multiplication for <em>scaling</em>. If a baby is about <m>0.6</m> meters long and their father is three times taller than the baby, the father is <m>0.6 \cdot 3 = 1.8</m> meters. There certainly aren't three babies here, but multiplying by three makes sense.</p>

        <todo>better picture, of course</todo>
        <figure>
            <image source = "images/scaling-baby-and-father.JPG" width = "50%" />
        </figure>

        <p>Of course, when we multiply larger values by hand, we use an algorithm. Again, there are many algorithms than that will work. Here a couple of examples:</p>

        <sidebyside>
            <p><me>
                \begin{array}{rrrrr}
                    \amp \amp 8 \amp 2 \amp 4 \\
                    \amp \times \amp \amp 5 \amp 2 \\
                    \hline{}
                    \amp 1 \amp 6 \amp 4 \amp 8 \\
                    4 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
                    \hline{}
                    4 \amp 2 \amp 8 \amp 4 \amp 8
                \end{array}
           </me></p>
           <p><me>
                \begin{array}{rrrrr}
                    \amp \amp 8 \amp 2 \amp 4 \\
                    \amp \times \amp \amp 5 \amp 2 \\
                    \hline{}
                    4 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                    \amp 1 \amp 6 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                    \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                    \amp \amp \amp 4 \amp 0 \\
                    \amp \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                    \amp \amp \amp \amp 8 \\
                    \hline{}
                    4 \amp 2 \amp 8 \amp 4 \amp 8 
                \end{array}
           </me></p> 
        </sidebyside>

        <p>Symbolically, there is more than one way to indicate multiplication. Any of the following symbolic expressions works:<me>0.6 \times 3 = (0.6)(3) = 0.6(3) = (0.6)3 = 0.6 * 3 = 0.6 \cdot 3</me> In algebra, the times symbol, <m>\times</m>, has fallen out of favor because it looks like the letter x, which we use to represent an unknown amount. Most mathematicians write parentheses or the dot, <m>\cdot</m>, to indicate multiplication. If you're typing, use parentheses or the asterisk, <m>*</m> for multiplication, and both people and computers will understand you.</p>

