    <subsection>
        <title>Signed Numbers</title>
        
        <p>As long as we compute using <term>whole numbers</term><mdash />which are the numbers <m>0, 1, 2, 3, 4</m>, etc.<mdash />and the order makes sensefor subtraction or division, the concepts of arithmetic are fairly well-understood by most people. But as soon as we consider reversing the order of subtraction, these concepts get more complicated. We use <term>signed numbers</term> to deal with these complications.</p>
        
        <p>In daily life, the signed numbers we see most often are temperatures. Most people on Earth use the Celsius scale; if you're not familiar with the Celsius temperature scale, see <xref ref="table-celsius-temperatures">Table</xref>.</p>

        <table xml:id="table-celsius-temperatures">
            <caption>Celsius temperatures.</caption>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell>Water boils</cell>
                    <cell><quantity><mag>100</mag><unit base="celsius" /></quantity></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Hot summer day</cell>
                    <cell><quantity><mag>32</mag><unit base="celsius" /></quantity></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Room temperature</cell>
                    <cell><quantity><mag>23</mag><unit base="celsius" /></quantity></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Cool autumn day</cell>
                    <cell><quantity><mag>13</mag><unit base="celsius" /></quantity></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Water freezes</cell>
                    <cell><quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="celsius" /></quantity></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Cold winter day</cell>
                    <cell><quantity><mag>-6</mag><unit base="celsius" /></quantity></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    <p>A thermometer displays temperatures above and below zero. In mathematics, values above and below zero are called <term>positive</term> and <term>negative numbers</term>, respectively. We can use temperature change to remind ourselves how adding and subtracting signed works.</p>

    <p>If it is 12 degrees Celsius below zero, and the temperature increases by 7 degrees Celsius to -5 degrees Celsius, there are a couple ways to write that change symbolically. If we think of this change as <q>more heat,</q> we have <me>-12 + 7 = -5,</me> but if we think of the same change as <q>less cold,</q> we have <me>12 - (-7) = -5.</me></p>
    </subsection>

